name: OpenHack: Code together, on anything
description:
JOIN US at our new meetup venue, INSPYRE Innovation Hub (*Formerly The Tech Garden*), for our new home in 2026.

Open Hack started as a friendly tech meetup at the Tech Garden in 2014, and we've held events (nearly) every month since. We're so happy to be back where it all started. Join us, won't you?

\-\-\-

The OpenHack elevator pitch:

* OpenHack is a casual social coding meetup with a simple purpose: Code together, on anything.

How OpenHack works:

* You can hack on anything! Any language, framework, public/open-source, personal projects, client work… anything!
* You don’t have to have an idea to hack on, you can come join someone else
* We’ll kick things off with a quick round of introductions, to say who you are, what you’re working on, and if you’d like help with your idea
* Food and drinks will be provided
* Feel free to join us - bring a laptop, a project, and a friend!

We welcome local developers and designers of all skill levels, interests, ages genders, you-name-it's to get together to write code or push pixels. We’ll provide good food, good people, and creative energy.

See more at https://syracuse.io/groups/open-hack/

What to bring

* A laptop if you're bringing a project, but totally not required

Important to know

* Please review our Code of Conduct before attending: https://syracuse.io/code-of-conduct/

name: Geek Night with the Syracuse Mets!!  Free tickets.
description:
Through my connection with Hugo Acosta of CNY Latino he has offered us 10 free tickets for a Syracuse Mets game!!!

Lets go with Friday, July 25 where the Mets play the Omaha Storm Chasers. The first 1,000 fans in attendance will receive Christmas Jersey Giveaway! Special Appearance by Santa Clause & his Elves! After the game, fans can enjoy a post-game fireworks show!

Lets meet somewhere at 6pm (won't get the freebie as probably have to show at 4) and gather as a group. We'll firm up the details as we get closer. First pitch is at 6:35.

Parking is NOT free. I think it's $5. Or you can park at Destiny or in the neighborhood south of the ballpark and walk over (I've done it). Or you can bike which I will. They do have bicycle racks.

Currently not admitting guests....but if there are seats available we can add them. Lets see how the signups go.

If it goes well, maybe this can be an annual event.

name: Computer Science Book club / Coffee & Code
description:
As I recall from the conversation that Mike, Kyle and I had from openhack; we are continuing with book club but at a slower pace. And you don't have to read the book to participate. We can chat about any aspects of tech. Our conversations typically went off on tangents anyway. Check us out. The next book has something to do with Wizards.

\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-
Comp Sci Book Club will continue discussion of our latest book: ***Code: The Hidden Language of Computer Hardware and Software Second Edition*** by Charles Petzold. We'll cover chapters 16-21 at the meeting. See you there!

Join the #compscibookclub channel in [Syracuse.io Slack](https://join.slack.com/t/syracuseio/shared_invite/zt-aw7rkg3q-2cgCecN524oOVarFJWMOPw) for the latest updates to the group!

\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-

Join our Comp Sci Book Club on Amazon and suggest books for future Meetups here: http://bit.ly/compscibookclub

Book description from [The Microsoft Press Store by Pearson](https://www.microsoftpressstore.com/store/code-the-hidden-language-of-computer-hardware-and-software-9780137909100):

"For more than 20 years, readers have delighted in Charles Petzold's illuminating story of the secret inner life of computers, and now he has revised it for this new age of computing. Cleverly illustrated and easy to understand, this is the book that cracks the mystery. You'll discover what flashlights, black cats, seesaws, and the ride of Paul Revere can teach you about computing, and how human ingenuity and our compulsion to communicate have shaped every electronic device we use."

name: SQL Saturday Syracuse Call for Volunteers
description:
**SQL Saturday Syracuse** is bringing free technical training to the local and regional communities of the Finger Lakes Region! To make an event like this possible, volunteers like YOU are needed!

We will have many tasks available for volunteers, all of which require no more than 1-2 hours of your time. The goal is for everyone to be able to help out while also being able to attend sessions and enjoy our conference.

Here are some of the tasks available for volunteers:
*Attendee bag assembly (1 week before SQL Saturday on an evening TBD)*
*Set up signage near our venue*
*Pick up and deliver breakfast*
*Set up/assist with breakfast/lunch/snacks/drinks*
*Set up (and periodically refill) coffee*
*Staff the registration table*
*Staff a session room or special lunch sessions*
*Staff the speaker room*
*Assist with raffles/closing*
*Cleanup*
*Photography*

More info on SQL Saturday: [https://sqlsaturday.com/2024-09-07-sqlsaturday1095/](https://sqlsaturday.com/2024-09-07-sqlsaturday1095/)

***Sign up to volunteer here: [https://www.eventbrite.com/e/sql-saturday-syracuse-call-for-volunteers-tickets-985832831537](https://www.eventbrite.com/e/sql-saturday-syracuse-call-for-volunteers-tickets-985832831537)***

*This Meetup is solely a placeholder to direct you to the volunteer sign-up. No need to register to attend as a volunteer on Meetup.*

Volunteering is GREATLY appreciated and I will ensure that each of you is personally thanked for your time and effort. Thank yous will include food, drinks, and some cool swag!

Don't forget to register for SQL Saturday!
THANK YOU!

* Professional Development

description:

* Avoiding ATS Pitfalls

* Current or soon to be tech job seekers!
* Individuals at all stages of their coding journey, from beginners to seasoned professionals looking to share input.
* Anyone interested in promoting gender diversity and inclusion within the tech industry.
* Enthusiasts seeking networking opportunities, knowledge sharing, and connection.

* your current resume (you don't have to share it, just for referencing)

Book description:
"Winner of the Pulitzer Prize and the American Book Award, ***The Soul of a New Machine*** was a bestseller on its first publication in 1981. With the touch of an expert thriller writer, Tracy Kidder recounts the feverish efforts of a team of Data General researchers to create a new 32-bit superminicomputer. A compelling account of individual sacrifice and human ingenuity, ***The Soul of a New Machine*** endures as the classic chronicle of the computer age and the masterminds behind its technological advances.

​“A superb book,” said Robert Pirsig, author of *Zen and the Art of Motorcycle Maintenance*. “All the incredible complexity and chaos and exploitation and loneliness and strange, half-mad beauty of this field are honestly and correctly drawn.” The *Washington Post* Book World said, “Kidder has created compelling entertainment. He offers a fast, painless, enjoyable means to an initial understanding of computers, allowing us to understand the complexity of machines we could only marvel at before, and to appreciate the skills of the people who create them.”"

Book description:
"Silicon Valley gets all the credit for digital creativity, but this account of the pre-PC world, when computing meant more than using mature consumer technology, challenges that triumphalism.

The invention of the personal computer liberated users from corporate mainframes and brought computing into homes. But throughout the 1960s and 1970s a diverse group of teachers and students working together on academic computing systems conducted many of the activities we now recognize as personal and social computing. Their networks were centered in New Hampshire, Minnesota, and Illinois, but they connected far-flung users. Joy Rankin draws on detailed records to explore how users exchanged messages, programmed music and poems, fostered communities, and developed computer games like The Oregon Trail. These unsung pioneers helped shape our digital world, just as much as the inventors, garage hobbyists, and eccentric billionaires of Palo Alto.

By imagining computing as an interactive commons, the early denizens of the digital realm seeded today’s debate about whether the internet should be a public utility and laid the groundwork for the concept of net neutrality. Rankin offers a radical precedent for a more democratic digital culture, and new models for the next generation of activists, educators, coders, and makers."

name: syr(js) | How Angular, Nx, Domain Driven Design Improve Large Development Teams
description:
ABOUT THE TALK
Nx is a monorepo tool for building software projects. Domain Driven Design (DDD) is a theoretical framework for organizing projects. Modern software development is a team sport. Combining Nx and DDD you can help your team work together by focussing on different layers of the application. You can create a coherent onboarding ramp for anyone being introduced into a large project without needing to write documentation. You can automatically enforce boundaries using a plugin for Nx that puts DDD into practice. In this talk you will be shown the path towards blissful teamwork. Will you choose to walk it?

name: Introduction to the Social Blockchain
description:
This Introduction to Social Blockchain class introduces how the integration of the blockchain on social platforms can help drive greater community engagement and creator independence. We will also discuss examples of how the social blockchain is being implemented including digital assets (creators with their own cryptocurrency or "social tokens") and organizations (decentralized communities without any leaders such as DAOs).

The blockchain is an immutable system of records of transactions that are maintained across several computers that are linked to a decentralized peer-to-peer network. Incentives, usually via the distribution of cryptocurrency, encourages people to maintain and utilize the blockchain.

The social blockchain refers to the application of social use cases on the blockchain, including games, social media applications, and community engagement platforms. For example, Microsoft is now using the blockchain to record contract creation, payment, and reconciliation transactions associated with gaming rights on its gaming platforms.

description:
The Cuse Video Game Jam is running from Friday Jan. 31 6PM-12AM, and then resume on Saturday Feb. 1 8AM-6PM. THE SITE WILL BE CLOSED OVERNIGHT AND THIS IS NOT AN OVERNIGHT HACKATHON.

Folks are welcome to continue to hack from home or a hotel room, but the venue will be closed from 12AM-8AM.

Friday 1/31 is starts off with snacks and introductions. Folks will then share what types of video or board game experience they have and pitch ideas for what type of game they want to make this weekend. Teams will then form and folks can start to build out what type of game they will make.

At 8 AM Saturday the ShareCuse venue opens again and folks can continue to hack with teams. Some snacks will be provided, there are restaurants and coffee shops in downtown Syracuse area that folks can visit, and folks are welcome to bring some food and drinks also. On Saturday at 6PM Hacking ends and the projects are shown to the group demoing and feedback.

Game creators are encouraged to stay for the whole event, but are welcome to come for part or all of either day! Syracuse has an awesome tradition of Hackathon's and building events, and we are excited to have an event focused specifically on game development!

The event is being held in the ShareCuse Coworking Space at:
224 Harrison St. It is in the Second Floor directly above Panini Restaurant and the front door to the building is directly to the left of Panini’s. ShareCuse is on the Second Floor in Suite 210 in Syracuse, NY.

name: Technology Learning Day Conference by Major League Hacking
description:
MLH's technology learning day conference is a global conference that allows the community to pick up new skills by experiencing a professional day of learning first-hand. Over the course of the day attendees will participate in a series of workshops where they’ll learn skills such as publishing their first website using AWS, sending their first SMS with Twilio, Blockchain, building their first game in Unity and more. This conference is for high schoolers, college students, coding newcomers, and technology professionals who want to know more about the world of technology from industry experts.

MLH's Local Hack Day is a series of simultaneous global events designed to spark a passion for technology in your local community. Spend the day getting hands-on experience and collaborating in a welcoming environment. Whether you are learning to code or are an expert hacker, Local Hack Day is perfect for you and your community. Learn new skills, build new projects, and share your creations.

This event is being held at one of Syracuse's newest premier co-working spaces... ShareCuse. Your attendance gives you first peek at what it would be like to be a part of the downtown Syracuse co-working scene for your business, personal projects, and freelancing needs.

Overall Timing

Doors open at 8AM, the opening ceremony starts at 9AM, and the first talk starts at 9:30AM. The event ends at around 7PM, you may come and go as you choose!

Parking

Parking is free in the parking lot behind 224 Harrison Street, off of Harrison Place. The gate will be open.

Snacks, Food

We will be providing breakfast, coffee, and snacks. Unfortunately, we were unable to provide lunch and dinner at this event but there are a lot of places to eat in Downtown. You are welcome to bring your own snacks and meals - there is a fridge to store all food.

Laptops

You are encouraged to bring a full-charged laptops! There will be several pair programming sessions as well as lectures.

Guests

You can bring as many guests as you wish, including children. There are small cubicles with see-through doors that (older) children can do homework in or bring toys or electronics to play with if they wish to not participate directly.

Here is the schedule (in PNG format and text) (there is a PDF version on the syracuse.io Slack in the general channel - we can guide you on how to sign up and navigate through the Syracuse.io slack tomorrow):

8:00 AM: Registration Begins, Breakfast

9:00 AM: Opening Ceremony

9:30 AM: Track 1: Twilio 101: Send Your First SMS Messages & Phone Calls - Dana McMullen (Careers in Code graduate, Web Developer with The Stand)

Track 2: Accelerate your C# Learning with Unity - Jason Scharf (Careers in Code Student Success Representative, Jingfu Chen, Industrial and Interactive Design student at Syracuse University, Unity Ambassador

11:00 AM: Break

11:30 AM: Track 1: Twilio 201: Build Your First App - Dana McMullen

Track 2: Accelerate your C# Learning with Unity - Jason Scharf (Careers in Code Student Success Representative, Jingfu Chen, Industrial and Interactive Design student at Syracuse University, Unity Ambassador

1:00 PM: Lunch break - You can bring your own meal or visit one of the Downtown restaurants

2:00 PM: Group Activity - Yu-Gi-Oh Game - JaQuay Winfield - Careers in Code graduate

3:00 PM: Track 1: Build a Mobile First, Responsive Portfolio Web Page using the W3.CSS Framework by Dana McMullen

Track 2: Drone Technology by Quindell Williams, Drone Instructor at PSLA and Mohawk Community College

Track 3: Bug-free Coding with SPARK ADA by Jennifer Tran, Software Developer at Metis Consulting Group

4:30 PM: Dinner

5:30 PM: Track 1: Alexa: Hacking with Amazon Alexa by Dana McMullen

Track 2: Blockchain Casino by Jennifer Tran

7:00 PM: Closing, Certifications of Completion Handed Out

Hope to see everyone tomorrow!

Dana, Jennifer, Jason, and Jesse

- State

- Render props (time permitting)
